## Development Setup

To help develop the new LigerBots website, you'll need to install three tools:

### 1\. Git

Git is a free, open-source, and distributed version control system that tracks changes in files, making it easier to manage and collaborate on software projects. It allows developers to work on code collaboratively, track changes, and revert to previous versions. Git is the most widely used version control system in the world and is considered the modern standard for software development. 

1. Install git for your platform.  
2. Clone a copy of the repo to a local directory of your choice.  
     
   Assuming you want to keep your source code under your home directory in a 'projects' directory.  
   * mkdir \-p \~/projects  
   * cd \~/projects  
   * git clone [https://github.com/raisch/ligerbots-website-frontend](https://github.com/raisch/ligerbots-website-frontend)  
   * cd ligerbots-website-frontend

### 2\. Node

Node.js is a runtime environment that executes JavaScript code outside a web browser. Built on Chrome's V8 JavaScript engine, it enables developers to use JavaScript for server-side scripting and build scalable network applications. Node.js operates on a single thread, using an event-driven, non-blocking I/O model that efficiently handles multiple concurrent requests. This makes it suitable for real-time applications, APIs, and microservices. While Node.js excels in I/O-intensive tasks, it may not be the best choice for CPU-heavy computations. 

1. Install node for your platform.  
2. Install 'n' \- node version manager  
   1. npm install \-g n  
3. Install 'pnpm' \- improved node package manager  
   1. npm i \-g pnpm  
4. Use n to upgrade to the current Long Term Support (lts) version of node (currently v22.15.0)  
   1. n lts 

### 3\. VS Code

VS Code (Visual Studio Code) is a free, powerful, and versatile code editor developed by Microsoft. It's a lightweight, cross-platform editor that supports various programming languages and comes with built-in features like syntax highlighting, debugging, and version control integration. VS Code also has a vast ecosystem of extensions, allowing users to customize it for their specific needs and languages. 

We use vscode (current version 1.99.3)  for development.

The team relies on several extensions which you'll need to load into your VS Code.

## Build and run a local development copy of the new website

**NOTE**: Before you can run the site locally, you'll need to get a "dot env" file from Coach Rob that contains "secret" configuration values that give you access to the Directus API. The file should be saved at the top-level of your source tree (perhaps \~/projects/ligerbots-website-frontend) and must be called '.env'.

Once you have that file in place, do the following from the command line.

* cd \~/projects/ligerbots-website-frontend  
* pnpm install  
* pnpm run dev  
* open http://localhost:4000

## About SvelteKit

Web development has come a long way since HTML and CSS were defined in the early 90's.

These days, when building complicated web sites, the standard approach is to think about your site as a collection of "components", each one of which is combination of structure (HTML), presentation (CSS), and functionality (JavaScript). These components, when downloaded and executed by your browser, modify the browser's Document Object Model (DOM) directly. So, the days when website development merely required some knowledge of HTML are in the past.

Using components in this way makes it easier to have multiple developers work on the same project without stepping on each other's toes since one developer usually works on one component at a time. It's for this reason that we've also structured this project using components.

You've probably heard of Angular ([https://angular.dev/](https://angular.dev/)), React ([https://react.dev/](https://react.dev/)), or Vue ([https://vuejs.org/](https://vuejs.org/)) which are popular web component frameworks and are widely used in development.

Instead of these, we've decided to use another framework called "Svelte" which is

***SVELTE** \[adjective\]  attractively thin, graceful and stylish*

*Svelte is a UI framework that uses a compiler to let you write breathtakingly concise components that do minimal work in the browser, using languages you already know — HTML, CSS and JavaScript. It’s a love letter to web development.*

The reason we're using Svelte is two-fold: 1\. Svelte components are much smaller and require far less overhead (other functions etc.) than other frameworks, and 2\. Svelte is light-years faster. This means that, once compiled, users will see pages from the new LigerBots web site faster than most other sites.

Along with Svelte, we're using a framework called SvelteKit that combines Svelte components with a build tool called Vite. (Pronounced "veet" from the French for "fast".)

Vite provides tooling to quickly iterate on your development work by automagically compiling and bundling all of your components. 

Vite uses rollup ([https://rollupjs.org/](https://rollupjs.org/)) for bundling which is similar to but more efficient than webpack in that it gathers all the javascript, css, and other resources that make up your web application so they can be made available to a web server of your choice. 

Sveltekit also provides scripts (in package.json)  that use vite to run your web site both in development mode (with real-time reloading or "watching") and in production preview. The scripts are:

* pnpm run dev  
  * build your components and run a web server on them in development mode  
* pnpm run preview  
  * build your components and run a static web server in production mode  
* pnpm run build  
  * build your components
